Well there you have it.  I leave it to you to judge for yourselves.  How does a veteran defend himself against this type person or persons?  We experienced a great deal of this type rhetoric in the 60's and 70's.  Certainly it had its impact upon some to the returning veterans, generally in the form of inciting someone's anger and not presenting a target!  Unresolved anger is generally turned inward and culminates in depression.  Dealing with someone like Spatz requires a deep sense of understanding of others behavior when they are so insecure that their thoughts mutate in order to protect themselves from reality.  Pity allows one to avoid the pitfall of anger.  If one can not find pity, then one can choose to simply step around the dog droppings on the busy sidewalk of life and move along!<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
